ce:section.ce:para:
In the present work, CDs were prepared using carbonization [43-45] of avocado seeds. Thermal treatment of dried and finely grounded avocado seed powder was performed using muffle furnace at 3 different temperatures (250, 400, and 600 °C) for 2 h each. Carbonization led to a dark black product at 250 °C (CD-250) and 400 °C (CD-400) as compared to dark gray at 600 °C (CD-600), which was further grounded and dispersed in deionized water, for subsequent sonication (4 h). The black color suspension was filtered using a filter paper (2.5
μ m
) followed by centrifugation at 13000 rpm for 30 min to remove large particles (schematic diagram corresponding to the synthesis process is included in Schematic S1a). The centrifuged supernatant (CDs) was stored in the refrigerator for further characterization. As the daylight illumination made the colloidal suspension of CD-250 / CD-400 and CD-600 appear as brownish and semi-transparent respectively, their appearance could be corelated to their dimension. The relevant information regarding QY measurements and calculations are included in supplementary information.

To verify the feasibility of our sensing nanoprobes for the detection of Cu2+ and Cr6+ in real-life applications, tap and river water sample from 2 different places, spiked with Cu2+/Cr6+ metal ions, were also tested under similar conditions. When tested in the river water, the sensing of Cr6+ and Cu2+ using CD-400 (Fig. 8
                        ) and CD-600 (Fig. 9

                        ) show superior sensing properties (summarized in Table 1
                        ) in comparison with test in deionized water, giving the lowest LOD of 0.04 nM (Cr6+) and 0.09 nM (Cu2+) with respect to the reported literature (Ref. to the comparison Table 2
                         and Table 3
                        ). Tests performed using the tap water are summarized in experimental section and corresponding analysis in Figs. S20 and S21. The sensitivity parameters corresponding to Cr+6 and Cu+2 detection of CDs in tap water are summarized in Table S4. Furthermore, interference tests (in the presence of different metal ions) corresponding to the detection of Cr6+ and Cu2+ showed a negligible interference (Fig. S22).
